    "content": "**Geopolitiks Snacks** — April 5, 2026\n\n---\n\n## ✈️ An American F-15E Is Down Over Iran. One Crew Member Is Still Missing.\n\nOn April 3, Iran shot down a U.S. Air Force F-15E Strike Eagle — the first American combat jet lost to enemy fire since the war began five weeks ago. US special forces rescued one crew member on Iranian soil. The other's fate remains unknown.\n\n- **The second plane:** An A-10 Thunderbolt II was also hit the same day, forcing the pilot to eject. He was recovered safely after the aircraft cleared Iranian airspace. Iran claimed it \"crashed into the Persian Gulf near the Strait of Hormuz.\"\n- **Israel stood down:** Israel reportedly postponed planned strikes in Iran to avoid interfering with the search and rescue operation. When Israel pauses its own military campaign to help recover a downed US pilot, the coalition dynamics are doing a lot of work.\n\n*Five weeks in and Iran just downed the first US combat jet to enemy fire. The White House's description of this as \"going very well\" is a load-bearing understatement.*\n\n**Sources:** [Haaretz](https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/iran/2026-04-03/ty-article/u-s-fighter-jet-shot-down-in-iran-search-underway-for-crew-u-s-official-says/0000019d-53de-d759-ab9d-7bdf7f960000) | [NPR](https://www.npr.org/2026/04/03/g-s1-116314/iran-hits-gulf-refineries-as-trump-warns-u-s-will-attack-iranian-bridges-power-plants) | [CNN](https://www.cnn.com/2026/04/04/world/live-news/iran-war-us-trump-oil)\n\n---\n\n## 🔥 Iran Hit Gulf Refineries. Trump Threatened Iranian Bridges and Power Plants.\n\nWeek five of the Iran war introduced a new escalation pattern: Iran targeting Gulf infrastructure, Trump threatening Iranian infrastructure, nobody de-escalating.\n\n- **Iran's moves:** Gulf oil refineries struck on April 3. Kuwait's water desalination and power plant \"significantly damaged\" on April 4. A Kuwait-flagged VLCC already hit by Iranian drone at Port of Dubai on March 31.\n- **Trump's response:** The President warned the US \"will attack Iranian bridges and power plants\" — a direct threat against civilian infrastructure. This is the phase where both sides trade escalatory statements designed to deter but that functionally raise the floor of acceptable violence.\n\n*Iran hits Gulf energy systems. Trump threatens Iranian power grids. The Strait is still partially blocked. Oil is at $109. (Fine. Probably fine.)*\n\n**Sources:** [NPR](https://www.npr.org/2026/04/03/g-s1-116314/iran-hits-gulf-refineries-as-trump-warns-u-s-will-attack-iranian-bridges-power-plants) | [The National](https://www.thenationalnews.com/news/mena/2026/04/04/live-iran-war-us-israel-mahshahr/)\n\n---\n\n## 🛢️ The Hormuz Blockade Cut Shipping Traffic 87%. The IEA Calls It the Worst Oil Shock in History.\n\nSince Iran imposed a selective blockade around March 15, traffic through the Strait of Hormuz has dropped from 150 ships per day to 10–20. The International Energy Agency has called it the worst supply shock in the history of the oil market.\n\n- **How Iran is managing it:** Ships are rerouted via Larak Island — a selective blockade, not a total closure. Iran controls who passes. That's leverage, not chaos.\n- **The numbers:** Oil at $109/barrel. US gas prices at $4.10/gallon and climbing. The strait normally handles 20% of global oil and LNG. An 87% traffic reduction is not an inconvenience — it is a structural problem for the global energy system.\n\n*The IEA has been tracking oil shocks since 1973. It has never called one \"the worst in history.\" That is new information.*\n\n**Sources:** [Wikipedia: 2026 Strait of Hormuz crisis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2026_Strait_of_Hormuz_crisis) | [MARAD](https://www.maritime.dot.gov/msci/2026-004-persian-gulf-strait-hormuz-and-gulf-oman-iranian-attacks-commercial-vessels)\n\n---\n\n## 🤝 Trump Is Going to China in April. Semiconductors and Rare Earths Are the Whole Conversation.\n\nA Trump state visit to Beijing is planned for April 2026, set up by the trade truce reached at the October 2025 APEC summit — which froze rare earth export controls and chip firm investigations for one year.\n\n- **What's on the table:** The US's leverage is advanced semiconductors — specifically Nvidia AI chip sales to China, still murky under current agreements. China's leverage is rare earths and battery materials, where Beijing controls a dominant share of global supply.\n- **The timing problem:** The one-year tariff truce expires around October 2026. Both sides are negotiating with one eye on domestic politics and one eye on who blinks first. An April summit produces a photo op and, maybe, an extension.\n\n*The two largest economies are meeting in Beijing to decide who controls the materials that run AI. No pressure.*\n\n**Sources:** [Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/u-s-and-china-agree-on-one-year-tariff-truce-including-semiconductor-and-rare-earth-breakthroughs-the-future-of-nvidia-ai-chip-sales-to-the-nation-remains-murky) | [China Briefing](https://www.china-briefing.com/news/trump-xi-meeting-outcomes-and-implications/)"
